The diesel version of the Siemens ICE was intended for the curvy tracks in 
the hillside regions of central and southern Germany ( Bavarian 
Forest/Thuringia) but in fact the tilting mechanism that was essential to 
be fast on those tracks never worked to perfection. After some time of 
being laid up the trains were sold to the Danish State Railway DSB. They 
are still painted in white but have the winged wheel of the DSB on their 
front. Their usage is to run between Copenhagen and Hamburg. The track is 
not electrified and part of it has of course to be done by ferry ( some 45 
minutes) . The entire trip takes about four hours and a half.﻿

Nasty modern souless plastic train. Can't beat an old one for reliability 
or comfort. I recall the ghastly 375 EMUs coming in when I worked for what 
was, in more civilised times, BR. Passengers would often wait for an "old 
one" i.e. MK1 EMU to appear, especially when we still had a good few of the 
CEPs and CIGs running. I spent years working those and only failed 
completely once. The awful 375 was another story. computerised and 
over-complicated, and flimsy.The first one I drove died at Crowhurst, a 
tiny station in the middle of nowhere, and the last one wouldn't even shut 
the pigging doors for us let alone go !﻿
